=========================================================
What happens internally?
=========================================================

Compiler generates something conceptually similar to

log<int,double,char,const char*>

↓

log<double,char,const char*>

↓

log<char,const char*>

↓

log<const char*>

↓

log()

Each recursive call creates another template instantiation
with one fewer template argument.

=========================================================
Parameter Pack Expansion
=========================================================

This line

log(args...);

expands the parameter pack.

Initially

args...

↓

2.3,'A',"Pavan"

Compiler converts

log(args...)

into

log(2.3,'A',"Pavan");

Next call

args...

↓

'A',"Pavan"

Compiler converts into

log('A',"Pavan");

Eventually

args...

↓

(empty)

Compiler converts into

log();

=========================================================
Most Asked Interview Questions
=========================================================

Q. Why is recursion used?

Because parameter packs cannot be processed directly.
We process one argument at a time.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Why do we need the base function?

To terminate recursion.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What is T?

First argument type.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What is Args...?

Remaining argument types.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What is args...?

Remaining function arguments.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What does

log(args...)

mean?

It expands the parameter pack and recursively calls log()
with the remaining arguments.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Does recursion happen at runtime?

Function calls happen at runtime.

The template instantiations are generated at compile time.

=========================================================
Interview Answer (30 seconds)
=========================================================

"Variadic templates use a template parameter pack (Args...) to accept
any number of arguments. In this recursive implementation, each call
processes the first argument and recursively calls itself with the
remaining arguments using parameter pack expansion (args...). The base
function with no parameters terminates the recursion. The compiler
generates a separate template instantiation for each recursive step,
while the recursive function calls execute at runtime."
